{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280605001/1949061201/0540.xml":{"full_text":"Editorials\u2014Features\nStamps\u2014Chess\nfflje fhntfiay Jstaf\nBooks\u2014Theaters\u2014Rod io\nMusic\u2014Art\u2014Bridge\nEIGHT PAGES\nWASHINGTON, P. C. JUNE 12, 1949\nCry Revived to Outlaw\nPolitical Contributions\nPayoff in Prestige Jobs Starts Debate\non Question of Having Government\nFinance All Campaigns\nBy Raymond P. Brandt\nPolitical payoffs with prestige positions in the Truman adminis\ntration in return for campaign contributions have revived talk that\nsuch donations be outlawed, with the Government bearing the cost\nof presidential contests.\nThe latest evidence of the cynical connection of big pocketbooks\nwith big politics has caused several national columnists to demand\nthat Congress, in the public in\nterest, appropriate money for con\ngressional as well as presidential\ncampaigns.\nIt has been pointed out, how\never, (1) that if the Federal Gov\nernment bore the cost \"many\nsplinter parties would emerge to\nenjoy lush campaign funds\u201d and\n(2) Congress might discriminate\nagainst bona fide parties having\nlarge followings.\nThere can be no doubt about\nthe evil, the question is about the\nremedy. The idea of Federal\nfinancing has a long history,, with\n\u2022its roots going back in the 19th\ncentury when the so-called \"male\nfactors of great wealth,\u201d repre\nt senting oil, steel, wool, the tariff\nprotected industries and the\nrailroads directed the course of\nGovernment from New York,\nPhiladelphia and Cleveland. The\nbig contributors paid their money\nand got their choice.\nThe Lewis Comeback\nIn more recent times the pattern\nof contributors changed, particu\nlarly in the Democratic Party, but\nthe expectation of a payoff re\nmains. In 1936 John L. Lewis and\nhis United Mine Workers contrib\nuted $450,000 and loaned $50,000\nto the Democrats. In 1937, after\nRoosevelt had denounced both the\nsteel companies and the miners\nfor work stoppages, Lewis intoned\nat a Labor Day speech:\n\u2018\u2018It ill behooves one who has\nsupped at labor's table and who\nhas been sheltered in labor's house\nto curse with equal fervor and fine\nimpartiality both labor and its ad\nversaries when they become locked\nin deadly embrace.\u201d\nAfter the 1944 campaign, Presi\ndent Truman tried to reward Ed\nwin W. Pauley with the undersec\nretaryship of the Navy for his own\nand his associates' contributions to\nthe campaign. The Senate refused\nto go along, and Pauley\u2019s nomina\ntion was withdrawn. Now there is\ntalk of rewarding Mrs. Perle Mesta\nand other contributors with am\nbassadorships for their prompt\ndollars.\nIn the old days Republican Boss\nMatt Quay of Pennsylvania de\nscribed the getting of such pres\ntige jobs as \"shaking the plum\ntree.\u201d The other side of the coin,\nor collecting, was called \"frying\nthe fat\u201d from the anticipating\ndonor.\nFederal Share Proposed\nBy 1907, however. Republican\nPresident Theodore Roosevelt, in\nhis annual message to Congress,\nproposed that the Federal Gov\nernment assume a part of the cost\nof conducting national campaigns.\n\u2018\u2018The need for collecting large\ncampaign funds would vanish,\u201d he\nwrote, \"if Congress provided an\nappropriation for the proper and\nlegitimate expenses of each of the\ngreat national parties. Then\nthe stipulation should be made\nthat no party receiving campaign\nfunds from the Treasury should\naccept more than a fixed amount\nfrom any individual subscriber or\ndonor; and the necessary publicity\n(for receipts and expenditures\ncould without difficulty be pro\nvided.\u201d\nWilliam Gibbs McAdoo, Presi\ndent Wilson\u2019s son-in-law and a\nformer Secretary of the Treasury,\nrevived the idea, with drastic\namendments, in the 1920 cam\npaign, by asserting that all private\ncontributions should be prohib\nited. He proposed:\n\"The expense of the national\nelections should be paid for out\nof the United States Treasury,\nand It should be made a crime for\na man to contribute a dollar to\ninfluence an election. Not only\nthen would we be spared the hu\nmiliation of begging for funds, but\nthe cost of campaigns would be\nreduced to one-fifth what they are\nnow. If the National Gov\nernment paid the expenses of\nthe national campaigns and speci\nfied the legitimate objects for\nwhich expenditures might be\nmade, politics would be purified\nenormously.\u201d\n\u2019No Bills Introduced\nThe late Bronson Cutting, the\nliberal Republican from New\nMexico, told a conference of Pro\ngressives in Washington in 1931:\n\u201cEvery one of us knows that\nthe sums of money spent ki cam\npaigns are not spent in oraer to\neducate the voters. On the con\ntrary they arc spent in order to\nconfuse voters. I am cer\ntain that the voters would be far\nbetter off and better educated if\nthese huge campaign funds were\neliminated and instead they were\ngiven a brief and definite state\nment of the attitude of the vari\nous candidates such as might be\nprovided under a publicly financed\nsystem of elections.\"\nThe Library of Congress Legis\nlative Reference 8ervice, the\nSenate librarian and the bill\nclerks of the two houses have no\nrecord of any bills having been\nseriously considered to carry out\nthe idea of Federal financing of\ncampaigns.\nApparently there are no prec\nedents for Federal legislation.\nAt a recent press conference\n9 President Truman said the idea\nwas discussed informally in the\nSenate committee when the\nHatch Act was under considera\ntion and discarded as imprac\nticable.\nGreat Britain offers no example,\nJ although the titles of nobility were\nsometimes the payoff for large\npolitical contributions. The Brlt\nfrh do not limit such contribution*\nor say how much a central party\norganization may spend, but hold\ndown the'expenditures of an in\ndividual candidacy for Parliament\nto 450 pounds ($1,800), plus about\na cent and a half for every voter\nregistered in the constituency. In\naddition, the candidate has the\nright to send post free to every\nregistered voter a letter of not\nmore than 2 ounces containing\ncampaign literature. Members of\nParliament do not have the frank\ning privileges our members of Con\ngress enjoy.\nMany Hands Involved\nAs indicated by the lack of\nbills to have the Treasury pay\ncampaign expenses, the ordinary\nmember of Congress does not seem\nto be interested in the idea, per\nhaps because of the complexities.\nThe practical politicians of the\nDemocratic and Republican na\ntional headquarters don\u2019t think\nmuch of the idea and can fore\nsee many difficulties in drafting\nlegislation that would not give ad\nvantage to the ingenious or the\nunscrupulous.\nOne Democratic committee\nspokesman points out that the\nnational committee is only one\nagency in a presidential campaign.\nThere are numerous collateral or\nganizations such as State and re\ngional committees, Senate and\nHouse political committees, vet\nerans\u2019 committees and so-called\nindependent committees, all of\nwhich collect and spend funds.\nEach committee is limited to\n$3,000,000 in a calendar year and\nindividual contributions are lim\nited to $5,000. The national com\nmittees of the two major parties\nspend about $1,000,000 annually\nfor routine work. In presidential\ncampaign years they usually spend\nabout the limit.\nIn 1943 the Smith-Connally Act\nforbade labor unions to contrib\nute to election campaigns but the\nfollowing year the CIO-PAC and\nthe NC-PAC spent $1,300,000\nwithout interference from the\njustice Department. The Taft\nHartley Act forbade unions to\ncontribute or expend union funds\nin a political campaign, but the\nPost-Dispatch noted in January\nthat labor groups reported that\nfor the 1948 campaign they had\nspent $1,291,000. This money\nwas contributed by individual\nunion members to political com\nmittees set up by the national\nand local unions. The CIO-PAC\nled the list with $510,003; the\nAFL League for Political Educa\ntion reported $312,196; the Ladies'\nGarment Workers\u2019 Committee,\n$240,532; the Railway Labor Po\nlitical League, $84,357, and the\nMachinists\u2019 Nonpartisan Political\nLeague, $33,043.\nTrade Union Role\nThe labor organizations\u2019 polit\nical committees are still at work\nfor the 1950 congressional and\nthe 1952 presidential campaigns.\nSuch committees bring up the\nquestion whether a Federal law\nprohibiting campaign contribu\ntions would violate the freedom-of\nspeech clause of the Constitution.\nTo take a simple case, could Con\ngress enact a valid law that would\nin effect prevent a trade union\nmember or a veteran from con\ntributing a dollar or so to a politi\ncal committee not the Demo\ncratic or Republican National\nCommittee\u2014to help elect a Presi\ndent, a Senator or a Representa\ntive who had promised legislation\nthe trade union member or the\nveteran favored? Or could Con\ngress effectively stop the \u201cinstitu\ntional\u201d or \u201ceducational\u201d adver\ntisements by such organizations\nas the National Association of\nManufacturers and some large\nbusiness concerns, which, although\nthey mention no candidates by\nname, are designed to influence\nvoters?\nOr as a States\u2019 right question,\ncould Congress say how much, if\nany. monea could be given to a\nState political organization al\nthough it is known that funds\ngiven to State candidates often\ninfluence presidential and con\ngressional elections?\nIt is easier to answer those who\nfear that splinter parties might\nget lush 'funds or that a major\nparty might be discriminated\nagainst if Congress voted cam\npaign funds. The allotment could\nbe on the popular votes cast in\nthe previous presidential and con\ngressional elections. At 1 cent a\nSpular vote in the 1948 campaign.\ns Democrats would get About\n$2,367,000, the Republicans, $2,\n164,000, the Dixiecrats, $100,000\nand the Wallaceite Progressives\nabout $100,000.\nUntil the constitutional question\nof freedom of speech, as it relates\nto the so-called voluntary or in\ndependent committees, is settled,\nthe party which got the support of\none or both of the two great pres\nsure groups of the country, the\ntrade unions and the veterans,\nwould have the advantage because\nthese two groups have the national\nand local machinery at hand to\ntake an aggressive part in any po\nlitical campaign affecting their in\nterests. They contribute something\nmore than money\u2014effective pre\ncinct work.\nFederal financing of campaigns\nmight prevent the payoff in cabi\nnet and diplomatic posts as well\nas stop the $100-a-plate lug of the\nJackson-Jefferson Day dinners.\nBut it might also cause many peo\nple, rich and poor, to take an even\nless interest In politics.\n*rr\u201cmriiii r** lm*\n2 Roosevelts on Political Scene\ni\nThey Could Become\nGovernors from\nBig Stotes\nBy Gould Lincoln\nThe impact of the Roosevelt*\non the history of the United States\nfor the last half century has been\nan amazing record\u2014and two more\nof the family are knocking at the\ndoor for high political preferment.\nJames Roosevelt, Democratic na\ntional committeeman for Cali\nfornia, is laying his plans to run\nfor Governor next year. Franklin\nD. Roosevelt. Jr., recently elected\nRepresentative from New York\u2019s\n20th congressional district, is a\npossible candidate for either Gov\nernor or Senator. In any event,\nit is expected that these two sons\nof the late President Franklin\nDelano Roosevelt, will face the\nelectorate of their respective\nStates in 1950. Franklin D., Jr.,\nmust run for his present seat in\nthe House, if he doe* not aspire\nto the Democratic nomination for\neither the 8enate or Governor and\nhe Intends to remain actively in\npolitics.\nIn 20 out of the last 50 years, a\nRoosevelt has been In the White\nHouse.1 Theodore Roosevelt was\nthe first\u2014a Republican. He served j\nvirtually eight years as President\u2014'\nand produced the \u201cSquare Deal,\";\nfor which he was roundly de-,\nnounced in conservative quarters.!\nTwenty years later Franklin D.'\nRoosevelt was elected President.'\nand was three times re-elected.\nWhen he died suddenly soon after\nhis fourth election, he had been\nin the White House a bit more\nthan 12 years. And he produced\nthe \u201cNew Deal,\u201d which aroused\neven more hatred than the Square\nDeal, but also more enthusiasm.\nTheodore Roosevelt did not give\nup easily. He sought to stage a\ncomeback in 1912, failed to win\nthe Republican presidential nomi\nnation against President William\nHoward Taft and running as a\ncandidate of the Bull Moose Party\nhe made certain the election of a\nDemocrat, Woodrow Wilson.\nThe presidential nominations of\n1952 are three years in the future.\nIf James Roosevelt makes good at\nthe polls in a contest for Governor\nof California, it is almost a cer\ntainty he will heave his hat in the\nring. Young Franklin D. Roose\nvelt, jr\u201e is 35 years old and by 1952\nwill be 38\u2014the same age at which\nGov. Dewey of New York made\nhis first bid for the Republican\npresidential nomination. If he\nwants to go to the Governor\u2019s\nchair in Albany and does not make\nthe try next year, he will have\nto wait until 1954 or 1958.\nMay Be Family Affair\nFew Democratic members of the\nHouse from New York have made\noutstanding records in recent\nyears. The spotlight, however,\nwill be turned on Franklin D., Jr.,\nthe minute he takes his seat. It\nIs conceivable\u2014whether probable\nor not\u2014that by the time 1952\nrolls around, a Roosevelt Governor\nof California may be facing across\nthe country a Roosevelt Governor\nof New York.\nSeveral hurdles confront the\nRoosevelts. In California, James\nRoosevelt must run the gauntlet\nof a primary election to win a\ngubernatorial nomination. In New\nYork, gubernatorial and senatorial\nnominations are made in party\nconvention\u2014usually in September,\nbefore the November general elec\ntion. Young Franklin D. has a\nyear in which to make good in the\nHouse and to convince Democratic\nleaders in the State that he is\nqualified for quick advancement.\nAs of today, George Luckey, a\nwealthy rancher, is most frequent\nly mentioned as a probable con\ntender for the Democratic guber\nnatorial nomination in California.\nMr. Luckey is vice-chairman of\nthe Democratic State Central\nCommittee, a supporter of Presi\ndent TVuman last year, and a\nrecent visitor at the White House.\nBoth the Roosevelts are war vet\nerans; James was a colonel of\nMarines and Franklin a com\nmander in the Navy, all of which\nwill do them no harm in their\nsallies into the field of politics.\nJames Roosevelt (left) and Representative Franklin D\nRoosevelt, jr\u201e both politically minded sons of the late President,\nmight possibly be Governors of California and .Yew York res\npectively by the time another presidential race gets under way\nThe late Theodore Roose\nvelt, Jr., who ran for Gov\nernor but never for President.\n\u2014AP Photo.\nJames Roosevelt was Democratic\nState chairman a year ago, and\nha\u00ab a considerable following among\nthe California Democrats\u2014as well\nas some enemies. He was elected\na delegate to the Democratic Na\ntional Convention as a Truman\ndelegate\u2014but he suddenly declared\nhimself for the nomination of Gen.\nDwight D. Eisenhower for Presi\ndent. Those were the days when\nthe ADA (Americans for Demo\ncratic Action) were giving Mr.\nTruman a cold shoulder; first, be\ncause they did not like the way\nMr. Truman had gotten rid of New\nDeal office holders and. second, be\ncause they did not believe that\nMr. Truman had a chance. Frank\nlin D., jr., went right along with\nhis brother James in his support\nof the draft-Elsenhower idea.\nWhen it became certain that Gen.\nEisenhower could not be drafted,\nboth Roosevelts turned in for Tru\nman\u2014 and James was elected\nDemocratic national committee\nman for California, while the con\nvention was in session.\nFavored in California\nPoliticians in California, Demo\ncratic and Republican, believe\nthat James Roosevelt will defeat\nGeorge. Luckey. if both are candi\ndates for the nomination for Gov\nernor. The race might become\ncomplicated, however, if other\ncandidates also entered the con\ntest. The Roosevelt name, as well\nas the fact that the Democratic\nParty in California has turned\nmore and more to the left of cen\nter, will help the son of the late\nPresident. Luckey is regarded as\na conservative Demoprat and\nRoosevelt, decidedly a liberal.\nGov. Warren, Republican, is re\ngarded as a probable contender\nfor a third term. He will be a\ntough customer for Roosevelt. In\n1946, Gov. Warren won not only\nthe Republican gubernatorial nom\nination but also the Democratic, in\nthe cross-filing system which\ncandidates employ in California.\nLast year, when he ran as Repub\nlican candidate for Vice President\non the Dewey ticket, and failed\nto carry his home State, his\nprestige suffered.\nThe Democrats in California\nhave a great advantage over the\nRepublicans in registrations, ex\nceeding Republican registration by\nabout 900.600. However, in 1946\n\u2019Gov. Warren won both nomina\ntions for Governor, and Senator\nKnowland. Republican, defeated\nWill Rogers, jr.. Democrat, son of\nthe humorist, by 200.000 votes in\nthe senatorial election. In the\n1948 election, the Truman-Barkley\nticket won over the Dewey-Warran\nin California by only 17,000\nReport has it that Mrs. Helen\nGahasan Douglas, a Democratic\nmember of the House now in her\nthird term, will seek the Demo\ncratic nomination for Senator\nnext year\u2014against the incumbent.\nDemocratic Senator Downey. If\nshe wins it\u2014and she may\u2014she and\nJames Roosevelt would make a\nstrong ticket in the general\nelection.\nAcross the continent, in New\nYork, the political picture is con\nfused. It is because it is so con\nfused that the possibility of a\nRoosevelt nomination is discussed.\nThe selection of the Democratic\nand Republican State tickets for\nnext year are very much up in\nthe air. It is suspected in some\nquarters that Gov. Dewey will\nmake another bid for Governor,\ndesiring to remain in politics. The\naged and ailing Senator Wagner,\nDemocrat, is not expected to be\na candidate to succeed himself\u2014\nhe has not been able to attend\nsessions of the Senate for many\nmonths. If he resigns before the\nend of the first week in July, an\nelection to fill the vacancy wdll\nbe held in November.\nSenator Wagner's son, Robert\nWagner, wants to run tor the\nSenate to succeed his father,\nand has been out seeking support\nof organized labor\u2014which thinks\nwuth pleasure of the Wagner Labor\nRelations Act. It has been under\nstood that the Senator will resign\nin time for a special election to\nfill his place this fall, provided the\nDemocratic leadership will agree\nto the nomination of his son.\nSo Franklin D., jr., now enter\ning the House in the place of the\nlate Representative Sol Bloom, to\nwhich Roosevelt was recently\nelected in a smashing victory over\nthe regular Democratic. Tammany\nnominee, must wait until there\nis a clarification of the situation\nbefore he can even begin to plan\nin his own mind his future course.\nSurprise Angles\nAdmittedly it would be a sur\nprising thing if the Democrats in\nNew York should pick young\nRoosevelt so soon for either a\ngubernatorial or senatorial nom\nination. The name, Franklin D.\nRoosevelt, however, would be\nworth many votes\u2014and if the\nDemocrats believed they were in\nbad case, they might risk all on\na Roosevelt,\nIt would be a coincidence, in\ndeed. if the Republican national\nstandard bearers of 1948. Gov.\nWarren in California and Gov.\nDewey in New York, running for\nre-election as Governor in their\nrespective States, should find\nthemselves confronted by Roose\nvelts\u2014sons of the late President.\nWhile two of President Frank\nlin D. Roosevelt s sons have gone\ninto politics in a big way. only\none. Theodore, jr.. of the sons\nof President Theodore Roosevelt\never made a bid for public office.\nTheodore, jr., died a general in\nactive service during the Second\n(See LINCOLN. Page C-2\nRussians Listen on 7 Million Radios\nBy Tom Whitney\nMOjSCOW.\u2014There are more\nthan 7,000,000 \"radio-receiving\npoints\u201d in the U. 8. 8. R\u201e ac\ncording to announced figures.\n(A \"radio-receiving point\u201d is\na point equipped to receive ra\ndio programs whether by vac\nuum-tube radio receiver of the\ntype used in American homes, or\nby wired loudspeaker systems.\nMany Soviet homes do, in fact,\nreceive programs over the\n\"wired-radio\u201d systems in op\neration in cities throughout the\nnation.)\nThis figure compares with 1,\n500,000 \u201cradio-receiving points\u201d\nin 1930 and 5.000,000 just be\nfore the war. Thus the radio\nreceiving network has grown\ngreatly in the last decade. It\nis still growing. During the\nlast two years about a million\n\"radio-receiving points\" have\nbeen added to the network each\nyear, including again both vac\nuum-tube receivers and wired\nloudspeakers.\nThe production of vacuum\ntube receivers is growing rap\nidly.\nThe network of broadcasting\nstations also is growing in the\nU. 8. 8. R.\n(In the United States it is\nestimated some 75,000,000 radio\nsets are in use\u2014all of the vac\nuum-tube type, and mere than\n39,000,000. or nearly 95 per\ncent of American homes ham\none or more sets. There are\n3,700 radio stations in opera\ntion, with four Nation-wide net\nworks serving U00 of them*nd\nregional networks providing\nprograms to hundreds more.)\nRussian broadcasts go out to\nthe U. S. S.*R. not only on the\nmedium or \u201cbroadcasting\" band\nused in the United States but\nalso on short waves and on long\nwaves. The vast ness of the\nnation makes it advisable to\nuse all these different bands to\nreach the country.\nRussian radio receivers are\nfreely bought and sold through\nout the country to any one who\nhas the cash. There are as\nmany different makes as there\nare factories.\nRussian broadcasts carry no\nadvertising or commercials.\nThey are financed by the gov\nernment in part out of a use\ntax on radio receivers.\n\u201cWired\u201d broadcasts are re\nceived over loud speakers plug\nged into the radio-program\ntransmission liras with which\nalmost every Moscow apartment\nla provided.\nSoviet stations in other cities\nthan Moscow have their own\nprograms in part and use in\naddition Moscow programs.\nThus the listener with a good\nset has a choice of programs.\nSince most Soviet receiving\nsets are also equipped with\nshortwave, reception facilities,\nit is also possible for the 8ovot\nlistener with a vacuum-tube\naet to get foreign abort wave\nprograms.\nTwo models of television sets\nare on sale now. Television Is\nlust getting a atari\n(Tha United Statoa has^aose\nthan 65 television stations on\nthe air and over 1,600,000 sets\nIn use).\nThe Soviet Union celebrates\nMay 7 every year as \"radio\nday.\" May 7 is the anni\nversary the Russians claim as\nthe date of the invention of\nradio by a Russian. Alexander\nPopov. They credit Popov\nwith demonstrating his radio\nreceiver before a meeting of\nthe Russian Physical-Chemical\nSociety. May 7, 1*95.\n(Dl\u00bbtr(but\u00bbd br th* AMori\u00ab*\u00bbd Fr**\u00bb\u00bb\nBritish Sec\nCompetition\nI From Reich\nIndustrial Comeback\nPoses Problems\nIn Exports\nBy Roland Bird\nLONDON \u2014The president of the\nBritish Board of Trade made a\nstatement in the House of Com\nmons recently on German compe\ntition in export markets At the\nvery moment, British exports\nwere breaking all records He\nhad previously listened to indus\ntries anxious to lay before him the\nfacts\u2014as they saw them\u2014of grow\ning German competition These\nrepresentations have been made\nwith an insistence which almost\nsuggests that Germany has made\na full-scale industrial recovery\nand has the whip hand in compe\ntition in the export markets.\nSome unkind critics of. British\nindustry have suggested that it is\nshouting long before it is hurt It\nhas certainly become rather un\nused to competition in the last 10\nyears. Controls and rationing at\nhome and a sellers market for\nexports have enabled British in\ndustry to go ahead with produc\ntion, often regardless of costs.\nThe first hint of competition is\nlike the first flurry of snow m\nwinter. It means tough weather\nahead\nThere are two mam complaints\nabout German competition The\nam is that it may be \u201cunfair'\u2014\nin other words, that It may be\nbolstered up by such devices as\nsubsidies and multiple exchange\nrates. The second is that German\nexports can be sold more cheaply\nthan British because German\nwage rates are lower.\nPrices Distorted\nUntil a short time ago the\njoint export import agency (which\nsupervises German trade on be\nhalf of military government'\nfixed the prices of German ex\nports by reference to prices of\nsimilar articles in world markets.\nLast summer, following the re\nform of German currency, a uni\nform conversion rate of 30 United\nStates cents to one deutschemark\nwas fixed. This rate has proved too\nhigh for some classes of German\nexports. For other classes of ex\nports, it may be unreasonably low.\nGerman prjees are still dis\ntorted. So are German wages.\nInternal German costs have not\nsettled down after the currency\nreform last June. They are much\nmore stable than they were, but\nIn some lines of production Ger\nmany could probably still afford\nto export at a much higher con\nversion rate.\nThe argument that German\nwages are unfairly low also fails\ntd survive examination. Increases\nin German wages have already\nbeen made since the 'stop\" was\nremoved last November. German\nearnings on the average are aovjt\nfit) per cent of British earning*.\nBut German productivity ner\nman Is certainly much lowu than\nBritish productivity.\nIt will take time before these\ndistortions in the German economic\nstructure are removed. In the next\nfew months the cost of replacing\nGerman stocks of materials will\nrise, while food will cost more.\nGerman wages will tend to rise as\nproductivity rises. There is no un\nassailable evidence of a persistent,\ndeliberate attempt at unfair com\npetition. through an unduly low\nconversion rate, through unfairly\nlow wages or through a system of\nspecific export subsidies\nMust Watch the West\nBritish exporters, nevertheless,\nare within theft rights in demand\ning that the government keep a\nclose watch lor sny emergence of\nunfair practices by Oerman in\ndustry. The fact that fears of\nOerman competition are out of\nproportion to the recovery in Ger\nmany's export capacity, however,\nsuggests that British Industry has\nsomething to learn about the\npart which Western Germany is\ndestined to play In European re\ncovery.\nGerman competition\u2014whatever\nmay be said of its long-run pos\nsibilities\u2014is in a very immature\nstage. The threat of competition\ntouches the edge of a few markets\nin which British exports have en\njoyed a clear run since the war\nThe final figures of German trade\nin 1848 are not yet available, but\nestimates suggest that exporta of\nraw materials and manufactures\nwere worth 8580.000.000. of which\none-third consisted of manufac\ntures Something less than 8200.\nOOOjOOO for German manufactures\nin 1848 compares with 85.512.000.\n000 for exports of British man\nufactures last year.\nOerman exports, which were\n\u00abSee BIRD Page C-5.\u00bb\nMoscow Watching Signs\nOf Recession in the l S.\nDefinite Trend Would Substantiate Snict\nReliance on Capitalistic Tailurc to\nT'orcc Popular Revolution\nIt Coastaatio* |rp\u00bba\nTin* reports of anprndms economic race*** sots no! \u00abr-h it the\nUnited Slates but in the major Marsha ii Plan count# a* a-.a\nbemg scanned eagerly m the Krrmiir\nSince the end of World War il the V ft h H has mUiM >*.n\ndisintegration of the capitalist system ratitej far aetua. I\u00ab\u00ab# of\narms, to bru